      "featured" : false,
      "content" : "<p>\n\tA recent mouse study at the UC Davis School of Veterinary Medicine demonstrated that a high-fat, or ketogenic, diet not only increases longevity, but improves physical strength.</p>\n<p>\n\t&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n\tJon Ramsey, senior author of the article in <em>Cell Metabolism </em>(September 2017), said &ldquo;We expected some differences, but I was impressed by the magnitude we observed &mdash; a 13 percent increase in median life span for the mice on a high-fat versus high-carb diet. In humans, that would be seven to 10 years. But equally important, those mice retained quality of health in later life.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>\n\t<strong>Source: </strong><a href=\"https://www.ucdavis.edu/news/eat-fat-live-longer\">https://www.ucdavis.edu/news/eat-fat-live-longer</a></p>\n<p>\n\t<a href=\"http://www.cell.com/cell-metabolism/fulltext/S1550-4131(17)30490-4\">http://www.cell.com/cell-metabolism/fulltext/S1550-4131(17)30490-4</a></p>",
